üß© Cloning Problems in Singleton Classes
----------------------------------------
A Singleton class must ensure that only one instance of the class ever exists in the JVM.
However, cloning can silently break this rule.

‚ö†Ô∏è How Cloning Breaks Singleton
----------------------------------------
Even if your class does not implement Cloneable, it can still inherit the behavior if:
‚Ä¢	Any parent class implements Cloneable
‚Ä¢	The parent class overrides and exposes the clone() method
Because of this:
‚Ä¢	The clone() method (from Object) can create a new instance, violating the singleton guarantee.
‚Ä¢	This leads to two separate objects: one created normally and one through cloning.

üßê Why This Happens
-----------------
‚Ä¢	clone() in Object (visible only in commons utils) is a protected method. (The protected methods of a class is visible only in the immediate subclass of the inheritance hierarchy)
‚Ä¢	Any class can override it and make it public, returning super.clone().
‚Ä¢	If your singleton does not stop this, a caller can simply do:
Printer p2 = (Printer) p1.clone(); // ‚ùå Breaks Singleton

‚úÖ How to Fix It
-----------------
To preserve Singleton behavior, explicitly block cloning:

@Override
protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
    throw new CloneNotSupportedException();
}

This ensures:
---------------
‚Ä¢	No one can clone the Singleton instance.
‚Ä¢	The JVM will enforce Singleton integrity at runtime.


üß† Important Note: Constructor Is Not Executed During Cloning
-------------------------------------------------------------
When an object is created through the cloning process, the JVM:
‚Ä¢	Creates a new object in memory
‚Ä¢	Copies all the existing field values from the original object
‚Ä¢	Does NOT call the constructor
Why?
-----
Because the clone is created by copying the internal object data (a field-by-field copy), not by constructing a new object through the normal instantiation path.

So:
‚Ä¢	The cloned object is already initialized with the original object‚Äôs data.
‚Ä¢	There is no need to execute the constructor separately.
‚Ä¢	Therefore, cloning bypasses constructors entirely.
This is exactly why cloning can break Singleton classes‚Äîbecause it silently creates a second object without invoking the constructor, bypassing the Singleton logic.


